        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "What a Mixture Model Is"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "A mixture model represents a probability distribution as a weighted sum of simpler component distributions. The Gaussian Mixture Model (GMM) uses Gaussian (normal) distributions as its components. Any data point x is assumed to have been generated by first picking one of K components at random — according to the mixing weights — and then drawing x from the chosen Gaussian."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "blockMath",
        "attrs": {
          "latex": "p(\\mathbf{x}) = \\sum_{k=1}^{K} \\pi_k \\, \\mathcal{N}(\\mathbf{x} \\mid \\boldsymbol{\\mu}_k, \\boldsymbol{\\Sigma}_k)"
        }
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "The three parameter sets per component are: the mixing weight πk (a scalar), the mean μk (a D-dimensional vector), and the covariance matrix Σk (a D×D positive-definite matrix). The weights must satisfy πk ≥ 0 and Σπk = 1."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "image",
        "attrs": {
          "src": "data:image/svg+xml;base64,",
          "alt": "Three Gaussian mixture components with their means, widths, and mixing weights summing to the overall mixture density"
        }
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "The Three Parameters per Component"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Mixing Weight πk"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "πk is the prior probability that a data point was generated by component k. It represents the fraction of the data belonging to that component. A component with π = 0.5 is twice as likely to have generated any given point as one with π = 0.25, before considering the actual data value."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Mean μk"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "μk is the centre of the k-th Gaussian. In clustering terms, it is the prototype location of that cluster. After fitting, μk converges to the centroid of the data points that component k is responsible for."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Covariance Matrix Σk"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Σk controls the shape, size, and orientation of the component. A full covariance matrix allows the component to be an arbitrary ellipsoid — it can tilt in any direction. Simpler covariance structures are often used to reduce the number of parameters:"
          }
        ]
      },
