      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Implementation"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "import numpy as np\nfrom scipy.stats import multivariate_normal\n\n\nclass GaussianMixtureModel:\n    \"\"\"GMM defined by K components with means, covariances, and mixing weights.\"\"\"\n\n    def __init__(self, means, covariances, weights):\n        \"\"\"\n        means:       list of K arrays of shape (D,)\n        covariances: list of K arrays of shape (D, D)\n        weights:     array of K non-negative values summing to 1\n        \"\"\"\n        assert np.isclose(sum(weights), 1.0), \"Mixing weights must sum to 1\"\n        self.K = len(means)\n        self.means       = means\n        self.covariances = covariances\n        self.weights     = np.array(weights)\n        self._components = [\n            multivariate_normal(mean=mu, cov=sigma)\n            for mu, sigma in zip(means, covariances)\n        ]\n\n    def pdf(self, x):\n        \"\"\"Evaluate p(x) = sum_k pi_k * N(x; mu_k, Sigma_k).\"\"\"\n        return sum(\n            pi * comp.pdf(x)\n            for pi, comp in zip(self.weights, self._components)\n        )\n\n    def sample(self, n: int):\n        \"\"\"Draw n samples from the mixture.\"\"\"\n        # Step 1: pick component indices according to pi.\n        component_idx = np.random.choice(self.K, size=n, p=self.weights)\n        # Step 2: draw one sample from the chosen component.\n        return np.array([\n            self._components[k].rvs()\n            for k in component_idx\n        ])\n\n\n# --- Example: 2-D GMM with 3 components ---\nD = 2\n\nmeans = [\n    np.array([0.0,  0.0]),\n    np.array([5.0,  1.0]),\n    np.array([2.0, -4.0]),\n]\n\ncovariances = [\n    np.array([[1.0, 0.5], [0.5, 1.0]]),   # tilted ellipsoid\n    np.array([[0.5, 0.0], [0.0, 2.0]]),   # axis-aligned\n    np.array([[1.5, 0.0], [0.0, 0.5]]),   # flattened horizontally\n]\n\nweights = [0.4, 0.35, 0.25]   # must sum to 1\n\ngmm = GaussianMixtureModel(means, covariances, weights)\n\n# Evaluate density at origin\nprint(f\"p([0, 0]) = {gmm.pdf(np.array([0.0, 0.0])):.4f}\")\n\n# Draw 500 samples\nsamples = gmm.sample(500)    # (500, 2)"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Scikit-learn Interface"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "In practice, GMM parameters are fitted from data using the EM algorithm. Scikit-learn exposes this via "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ],
            "text": "GaussianMixture"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": ". Once fitted, the same three parameter sets are available as attributes."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "from sklearn.mixture import GaussianMixture\nimport numpy as np\n\n# Synthetic data: two blobs\nrng = np.random.default_rng(42)\nX = np.vstack([\n    rng.multivariate_normal([0, 0], [[1, 0], [0, 1]], size=200),\n    rng.multivariate_normal([5, 5], [[2, 0.5], [0.5, 1]], size=300),\n])\n\n# Fit a 2-component GMM with full covariance matrices\ngmm = GaussianMixture(n_components=2, covariance_type='full',\n                      random_state=0)\ngmm.fit(X)\n\n# Inspect the three parameter sets for each component\nprint(\"Mixing weights (pi):\", gmm.weights_)\n# [0.401  0.599]   (ground truth: 0.4 / 0.6)\n\nprint(\"Means (mu):\\n\", gmm.means_)\n# [[~0, ~0], [~5, ~5]]\n\nprint(\"Covariances (Sigma):\\n\", gmm.covariances_)\n# Shapes (2, 2, 2) — one 2×2 matrix per component\n\n# Evaluate p(x) for a single point\np = np.exp(gmm.score_samples([[2.5, 2.5]]))\nprint(f\"p([2.5, 2.5]) = {p[0]:.4f}\")"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Choosing the Number of Components K"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "K is a hyperparameter, not learned from data directly. Two standard model-selection criteria compare the log-likelihood against a penalty for model complexity:"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "bulletList",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ],
                    "text": "BIC (Bayesian Information Criterion):"
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": " penalises by p·ln(N) where p is the number of free parameters. Tends to prefer fewer components on smaller datasets."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ],
                    "text": "AIC (Akaike Information Criterion):"
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": " penalises by 2p. Less conservative — tends to pick a larger K than BIC."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "from sklearn.mixture import GaussianMixture\nimport numpy as np\n\n# Fit GMMs for K = 1..8 and compare BIC scores (lower is better)\nbic_scores = []\nfor k in range(1, 9):\n    gmm = GaussianMixture(n_components=k, covariance_type='full',\n                          random_state=0)\n    gmm.fit(X)\n    bic_scores.append((k, gmm.bic(X)))\n\nbest_k, best_bic = min(bic_scores, key=lambda t: t[1])\nprint(f\"Best K by BIC: {best_k}  (BIC = {best_bic:.1f})\")"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Component Responsibilities"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "After fitting, each data point can be assigned a responsibility (posterior probability) for each component — the soft analogue of cluster membership in k-means:"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "blockMath",
        "attrs": {
          "latex": "r_{nk} = \\frac{\\pi_k \\, \\mathcal{N}(\\mathbf{x}_n \\mid \\boldsymbol{\\mu}_k, \\boldsymbol{\\Sigma}_k)}{\\sum_{j=1}^{K} \\pi_j \\, \\mathcal{N}(\\mathbf{x}_n \\mid \\boldsymbol{\\mu}_j, \\boldsymbol{\\Sigma}_j)}"
        }
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "This is the E-step of the EM algorithm. A point near the centre of component k gets high rnk ≈ 1; a point equidistant between two components gets rnk ≈ 0.5 for each. The EM algorithm then re-estimates μk, Σk, and πk using these soft assignments (M-step), and iterates until convergence. This is explained fully in the Expectation-Maximisation sub-subtopic."
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
  }
